    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_593941039" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/593941039" />
    <a title="Mitch" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2946068-mitch"><img alt="Mitch" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570799984p2/2946068.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/593941039?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mitch" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mitch" href="/user/show/2946068-mitch">Mitch</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2946068-mitch?shelf=just-fiction">just-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer593941039" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5115335393833181307">Actually, I&apos;d classify this just as fiction more than as literary fiction.<br/><br/>What&apos;s good here is the &apos;Indian-ness&apos; of the storyline and characters. <br/><br/>The story is a window into the intertwined lives of a three-story apartment building in Mumbai, and the thread that somewhat ties them together is the death process of a man who has the paid-for right to live on their stair landing and run errands for them. (This is based on a real-life situation from the author&apos;s past.)<br/><br/>What&apos;s interesting is that the au</span>
  <span id="freeText5115335393833181307" style="display:none">Actually, I'd classify this just as fiction more than as literary fiction.<br /><br />What's good here is the 'Indian-ness' of the storyline and characters. <br /><br />The story is a window into the intertwined lives of a three-story apartment building in Mumbai, and the thread that somewhat ties them together is the death process of a man who has the paid-for right to live on their stair landing and run errands for them. (This is based on a real-life situation from the author's past.)<br /><br />What's interesting is that the author creates a subjective account of the death process...how Vishnu experiences his increasing detachment from the earth and his ascension to his next incarnation.<br /><br />However...the other apartment dwellers seem to embody much that is despicable in human nature. They lie, backstab, steal and cause one another a lot of grief in their pettiness. They are not fun to get to know.<br /><br />Secondly, when the book ends, not much is actually resolved. Plot lines just sort of stop, and there you are. <br /><br />At times the author seems to be overly obvious in what he is doing as well. Here he is building suspense, there he is drawing out the drama for effect... While these things should be happening, they shouldn't intrude repeatedly into the reader's consciousness. But they do.<br /><br />Hence, the two-star rating. </span>
  <a data-text-id="5115335393833181307" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


